Subsection 1956(f) defines the jurisdiction of United States courts over extraterritorial acts which fall within the scope of Section 1956. The two preconditions for extraterritorial jurisdiction are: (I) The conduct was committed by a United States citizen or, in the case of a non-United States citizen, the conduct occurred in part in the United States, and (2) the transaction or series of transactions involved funds or monetary instruments of a value exceeding $i0,000.
